The MVC (Model-View-Controller) pattern is a widely used architectural pattern in software development that separates an application into three interconnected components. 

**Model:**
The Model represents the data and business logic of the application. It is responsible for managing the data and performing calculations. The Model is typically implemented as a class that encapsulates the data and provides methods for manipulating it.

**View:**
The View is responsible for rendering the user interface of the application. It is typically implemented as a class that displays the data provided by the Model.

**Controller:**
The Controller acts as an intermediary between the Model and the View. It receives input from the user, updates the Model accordingly, and then updates the View to reflect the changes.

